doc.after: Egypt signed the Rio Convention on Biological Diversity on 9 June 1992, and became a party to the convention on 2 June 1994.[109] It has subsequently produced a National Biodiversity Strategy and Action Plan, which was received by the convention on 31 July 1998.[110] Where many CBD National Biodiversity Strategy and Action Plans neglect biological kingdoms apart from animals and plants,[111] Egypt's plan was unusual in providing balanced information about all forms of life.
